WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:01.070 align:middle line:90%


00:00:01.070 --> 00:00:03.320 align:middle line:84%
>>Christine Arena has
been a managing director

00:00:03.320 --> 00:00:05.690 align:middle line:84%
and strategic director
in the business world,

00:00:05.690 --> 00:00:08.630 align:middle line:84%
as well as co-founding
a variety of businesses.

00:00:08.630 --> 00:00:11.100 align:middle line:84%
As she observed the various
corporate strategies,

00:00:11.100 --> 00:00:13.910 align:middle line:84%
she began to see an
interesting picture emerge.

00:00:13.910 --> 00:00:17.460 align:middle line:84%
Companies that had core values
reflecting a win-win regarding

00:00:17.460 --> 00:00:19.560 align:middle line:84%
profits, people,
and the environment

00:00:19.560 --> 00:00:21.160 align:middle line:90%
seemed to perform best.

00:00:21.160 --> 00:00:23.480 align:middle line:84%
She followed up this
observation by interviewing

00:00:23.480 --> 00:00:27.100 align:middle line:84%
company CEOs committed to
high purpose business, which

00:00:27.100 --> 00:00:30.330 align:middle line:84%
became the framework for
her book Cause For Success.

00:00:30.330 --> 00:00:32.400 align:middle line:84%
In this interview she
talks about the road

00:00:32.400 --> 00:00:34.510 align:middle line:84%
to becoming a high
purpose company

00:00:34.510 --> 00:00:36.984 align:middle line:84%
and how we, the consumer,
can prompt industry

00:00:36.984 --> 00:00:37.900 align:middle line:90%
toward this direction.

00:00:37.900 --> 00:00:47.654 align:middle line:90%


00:00:47.654 --> 00:00:50.710 align:middle line:84%
>>What inspired you to
put Cause For Success

00:00:50.710 --> 00:00:53.390 align:middle line:84%
together and analyze
these different business

00:00:53.390 --> 00:00:56.310 align:middle line:84%
models of conscious
business practice?

00:00:56.310 --> 00:00:58.200 align:middle line:84%
>>It sounds like an
oxymoron to a lot

00:00:58.200 --> 00:00:59.780 align:middle line:90%
of people, conscious business.

00:00:59.780 --> 00:01:03.730 align:middle line:84%
I was working for 13
years for corporations,

00:01:03.730 --> 00:01:06.490 align:middle line:84%
trying to help them
determine what people needed,

00:01:06.490 --> 00:01:09.580 align:middle line:84%
to help them better market
their products or services,

00:01:09.580 --> 00:01:10.840 align:middle line:90%
as the case may be.

00:01:10.840 --> 00:01:12.780 align:middle line:84%
And I think after
a while of trying

00:01:12.780 --> 00:01:16.170 align:middle line:84%
to unearth these very
superficial needs that people

00:01:16.170 --> 00:01:21.300 align:middle line:84%
had, like the need to be desired
or the need to feel powerful,

00:01:21.300 --> 00:01:23.820 align:middle line:84%
I sort of thought, you know,
what about the companies that

00:01:23.820 --> 00:01:26.710 align:middle line:84%
are out there serving really
fundamental human needs,

00:01:26.710 --> 00:01:29.320 align:middle line:84%
like the need to
stop global warming

00:01:29.320 --> 00:01:35.239 align:middle line:84%
or find a cure for cancer
or stop the poverty problem?

00:01:35.239 --> 00:01:37.780 align:middle line:84%
And the truth is there are a
lot of companies out there doing

00:01:37.780 --> 00:01:40.800 align:middle line:84%
that, so I thought I
wanted to write about them.

00:01:40.800 --> 00:01:43.360 align:middle line:84%
>>So let's begin
at the beginning

00:01:43.360 --> 00:01:46.160 align:middle line:84%
then and talk about
a couple of examples

00:01:46.160 --> 00:01:48.820 align:middle line:84%
that you were particularly
inspired by that you feature

00:01:48.820 --> 00:01:50.220 align:middle line:90%
in the Cause For Success.

00:01:50.220 --> 00:01:53.630 align:middle line:84%
>>Well, I think the most
notable example in the book,

00:01:53.630 --> 00:01:56.962 align:middle line:84%
there are several, but British
Petroleum is certainly one, BP.

00:01:56.962 --> 00:01:59.340 align:middle line:84%
And that's a company that's
hugely controversial.

00:01:59.340 --> 00:02:02.220 align:middle line:84%
And actually, I've been
criticized for putting them

00:02:02.220 --> 00:02:04.270 align:middle line:84%
in the book because
people think,

00:02:04.270 --> 00:02:05.580 align:middle line:90%
well, this is an oil giant.

00:02:05.580 --> 00:02:09.190 align:middle line:84%
I mean, this is a company that
releases 80.5 million tons

00:02:09.190 --> 00:02:11.420 align:middle line:84%
of CO2 into the
atmosphere every year.

00:02:11.420 --> 00:02:15.700 align:middle line:84%
They reported 20 fatalities
among their work force

00:02:15.700 --> 00:02:18.950 align:middle line:84%
and contractors last year
for on the job accidents.

00:02:18.950 --> 00:02:21.720 align:middle line:84%
So they're not a perfect
company with a perfect record.

00:02:21.720 --> 00:02:23.970 align:middle line:84%
But they were the
first oil giant

00:02:23.970 --> 00:02:27.320 align:middle line:84%
to admit, when
nobody else would,

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:29.820 align:middle line:84%
that global warming was
a real and serious threat

00:02:29.820 --> 00:02:32.600 align:middle line:84%
and that it was incumbent upon
every company in its category

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:34.400 align:middle line:90%
to do something about it.

00:02:34.400 --> 00:02:37.100 align:middle line:84%
Well now, today, I
mean, the company

00:02:37.100 --> 00:02:41.020 align:middle line:84%
has reduced its CO2
emissions by 10%.

00:02:41.020 --> 00:02:44.390 align:middle line:84%
It's become the world's leading
provider of cleaner burning

00:02:44.390 --> 00:02:44.890 align:middle line:90%
fuels.

00:02:44.890 --> 00:02:48.990 align:middle line:84%
It's the second largest producer
of solar panels on the world.

00:02:48.990 --> 00:02:53.090 align:middle line:84%
And now, every other oil
giant is following BP's lead.

00:02:53.090 --> 00:02:56.220 align:middle line:84%
So in a sense, even though
it's not a perfect company,

00:02:56.220 --> 00:02:58.420 align:middle line:84%
it's certainly a
leader in this area.

00:02:58.420 --> 00:03:00.430 align:middle line:84%
And I think that that's
a distinction that

00:03:00.430 --> 00:03:01.190 align:middle line:90%
needs to be made.

00:03:01.190 --> 00:03:02.750 align:middle line:90%
You know what it is?

00:03:02.750 --> 00:03:05.820 align:middle line:84%
I've found that there is
a new form of success,

00:03:05.820 --> 00:03:08.610 align:middle line:84%
and that form of success
is not about perfection.

00:03:08.610 --> 00:03:11.500 align:middle line:84%
It's about the
pursuit of perfection.

00:03:11.500 --> 00:03:17.530 align:middle line:84%
It's about a continual cycle
of really tough self-evaluation

00:03:17.530 --> 00:03:20.270 align:middle line:90%
and continual self-improvement.

00:03:20.270 --> 00:03:24.990 align:middle line:84%
And companies like BP, Hewlett
Packard, The Body Shop,

00:03:24.990 --> 00:03:27.790 align:middle line:84%
Stonyfield Farm, the
Grameen Bank, the companies

00:03:27.790 --> 00:03:32.620 align:middle line:84%
that I feature in this book are
all engaged in that process.

00:03:32.620 --> 00:03:35.430 align:middle line:84%
And so it really requires
companies to look themselves

00:03:35.430 --> 00:03:39.747 align:middle line:84%
in the mirror and
assess the real impact

00:03:39.747 --> 00:03:41.330 align:middle line:84%
the whole of their
business activities

00:03:41.330 --> 00:03:43.542 align:middle line:90%
have on the rest of the world.

00:03:43.542 --> 00:03:45.000 align:middle line:84%
And it requires
companies to answer

00:03:45.000 --> 00:03:46.710 align:middle line:84%
a really difficult
question, which

00:03:46.710 --> 00:03:51.070 align:middle line:84%
is, are we fundamentally helping
people or harming people?

00:03:51.070 --> 00:03:52.640 align:middle line:84%
I mean, at the end
of the day, that's

00:03:52.640 --> 00:03:57.710 align:middle line:84%
the question that should be
asked by every business leader.

00:03:57.710 --> 00:03:59.620 align:middle line:84%
>>We didn't say
this right up front,

00:03:59.620 --> 00:04:03.830 align:middle line:84%
which should have been said,
which is Cause For Success is

00:04:03.830 --> 00:04:06.310 align:middle line:84%
about companies who put
their profits second

00:04:06.310 --> 00:04:07.610 align:middle line:90%
and their purpose--

00:04:07.610 --> 00:04:09.630 align:middle line:90%
And you call this high purpose.

00:04:09.630 --> 00:04:13.770 align:middle line:84%
--first and ended up coming
in first financially.

00:04:13.770 --> 00:04:14.790 align:middle line:90%
>>They did.

00:04:14.790 --> 00:04:17.399 align:middle line:84%
They came in first and
surpassed their competitors

00:04:17.399 --> 00:04:21.112 align:middle line:84%
in the marketplace by putting
a social problem first.

00:04:21.112 --> 00:04:22.695 align:middle line:84%
And high purpose
companies are unique.

00:04:22.695 --> 00:04:27.280 align:middle line:84%
They're a unique breed
because the litmus test is,

00:04:27.280 --> 00:04:31.420 align:middle line:84%
if you removed the company's
higher purpose or its cause,

00:04:31.420 --> 00:04:33.810 align:middle line:84%
its crusade, whether
it's a social crusade

00:04:33.810 --> 00:04:37.170 align:middle line:84%
or an environmental
crusade, would the company

00:04:37.170 --> 00:04:39.450 align:middle line:84%
continue to compete
as efficiently?

00:04:39.450 --> 00:04:41.830 align:middle line:84%
For high purpose companies,
the answer is no.

00:04:41.830 --> 00:04:45.340 align:middle line:84%
If you took the green
aspect away from BP,

00:04:45.340 --> 00:04:47.860 align:middle line:84%
I asked Lord John Brown,
the group chief executive

00:04:47.860 --> 00:04:50.270 align:middle line:84%
of that company what would
happen if we did that.

00:04:50.270 --> 00:04:52.500 align:middle line:84%
And he said, we would
no longer be BP.

00:04:52.500 --> 00:04:55.300 align:middle line:84%
I mean our whole
growth strategy,

00:04:55.300 --> 00:04:56.930 align:middle line:84%
our distinction
in the marketplace

00:04:56.930 --> 00:05:00.670 align:middle line:84%
is contingent upon our
ability to progress

00:05:00.670 --> 00:05:04.290 align:middle line:84%
in a social and
environmentally friendly way.

00:05:04.290 --> 00:05:06.160 align:middle line:84%
So it's really core
to the company.

00:05:06.160 --> 00:05:10.440 align:middle line:84%
And that's true for a lot more
companies than people think.

00:05:10.440 --> 00:05:13.290 align:middle line:84%
People really think that
corporations are evil,

00:05:13.290 --> 00:05:14.900 align:middle line:90%
especially big corporations.

00:05:14.900 --> 00:05:18.130 align:middle line:84%
But you know, I have to say that
that's becoming less and less

00:05:18.130 --> 00:05:20.810 align:middle line:84%
true because society's
putting a lot of pressure

00:05:20.810 --> 00:05:23.220 align:middle line:90%
on companies to act better.

00:05:23.220 --> 00:05:27.020 align:middle line:84%
>>Before we get into other
specific companies and what

00:05:27.020 --> 00:05:33.980 align:middle line:84%
inspired them and what the
net effect ended up becoming,

00:05:33.980 --> 00:05:36.530 align:middle line:84%
how can companies at
this point in time--

00:05:36.530 --> 00:05:38.450 align:middle line:84%
Everybody in the oil
industry certainly

00:05:38.450 --> 00:05:43.100 align:middle line:84%
has to know what BP is up to
and how it has benefited them.

00:05:43.100 --> 00:05:45.730 align:middle line:84%
--what do you think the
major points of resistance

00:05:45.730 --> 00:05:49.760 align:middle line:84%
are to other companies following
suit at this time, then?

00:05:49.760 --> 00:05:54.660 align:middle line:84%
>>You know, it's like what is
the major point of resistance

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:56.740 align:middle line:90%
to any form of human progress?

00:05:56.740 --> 00:05:58.340 align:middle line:90%
It's fear.

00:05:58.340 --> 00:06:01.750 align:middle line:84%
And in some cases,
it's laziness.

00:06:01.750 --> 00:06:03.400 align:middle line:90%
But fear is a big one.

00:06:03.400 --> 00:06:06.160 align:middle line:84%
And I'll use an example,
a controversial example.

00:06:06.160 --> 00:06:08.300 align:middle line:84%
Walmart is an
interesting company

00:06:08.300 --> 00:06:09.756 align:middle line:90%
because it's always in the news.

00:06:09.756 --> 00:06:13.840 align:middle line:84%
It's constantly being criticized
for its negative impact

00:06:13.840 --> 00:06:17.190 align:middle line:84%
on society, for its
treatment of employees,

00:06:17.190 --> 00:06:20.920 align:middle line:84%
for its contribution to the
outsourcing of American jobs

00:06:20.920 --> 00:06:22.400 align:middle line:90%
and an array of problems.

00:06:22.400 --> 00:06:25.850 align:middle line:84%
It's also responsible
for some great things.

00:06:25.850 --> 00:06:28.990 align:middle line:84%
Realistically, it
employs 10 million people

00:06:28.990 --> 00:06:30.210 align:middle line:90%
around the world.

00:06:30.210 --> 00:06:35.610 align:middle line:84%
But what's really interesting
is that that company just

00:06:35.610 --> 00:06:39.630 align:middle line:84%
waged a very expensive
advertising campaign designed

00:06:39.630 --> 00:06:42.820 align:middle line:84%
to refute all of the
controversy against it.

00:06:42.820 --> 00:06:44.940 align:middle line:84%
Anyone who's spoken
out against Walmart

00:06:44.940 --> 00:06:46.610 align:middle line:84%
in the last couple
of years, and granted

00:06:46.610 --> 00:06:47.693 align:middle line:90%
there are a lot of people.

00:06:47.693 --> 00:06:49.300 align:middle line:84%
There are 5,000
outstanding lawsuits

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:51.750 align:middle line:84%
against the company
at this time.

00:06:51.750 --> 00:06:54.190 align:middle line:84%
The company characterized
those assaults

00:06:54.190 --> 00:06:57.550 align:middle line:90%
as urban myths, urban legends.

00:06:57.550 --> 00:07:00.480 align:middle line:84%
So they really kind
of brushed over

00:07:00.480 --> 00:07:03.850 align:middle line:84%
a lot of those sometimes
substantive comments

00:07:03.850 --> 00:07:05.130 align:middle line:90%
and criticisms.

00:07:05.130 --> 00:07:10.170 align:middle line:84%
Now, that's very different
if you put that example

00:07:10.170 --> 00:07:12.030 align:middle line:90%
head to head with the Gap.

00:07:12.030 --> 00:07:15.230 align:middle line:84%
That's another company that's
topped anti-sweatshop activists

00:07:15.230 --> 00:07:21.010 align:middle line:84%
lists for 20 years
practically, 10 years at least.

00:07:21.010 --> 00:07:23.410 align:middle line:84%
That company just released
a really scathing report

00:07:23.410 --> 00:07:25.080 align:middle line:90%
about itself.

00:07:25.080 --> 00:07:29.340 align:middle line:84%
It admitted that there
were human rights problems.

00:07:29.340 --> 00:07:31.390 align:middle line:90%
There were labor problems.

00:07:31.390 --> 00:07:35.440 align:middle line:84%
There were unfair competition
problems or issues

00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:38.980 align:middle line:84%
in its factories
that were negative.

00:07:38.980 --> 00:07:41.142 align:middle line:84%
And instead of hiding
that and pretending

00:07:41.142 --> 00:07:43.225 align:middle line:84%
like it was complying with
the law, which it was--

00:07:43.225 --> 00:07:44.820 align:middle line:90%
It was not breaking the law.

00:07:44.820 --> 00:07:47.210 align:middle line:90%
--it opened up a can of worms.

00:07:47.210 --> 00:07:49.990 align:middle line:84%
And it invited people
to go, wait a minute.

00:07:49.990 --> 00:07:51.640 align:middle line:90%
You can't do that.

00:07:51.640 --> 00:07:53.340 align:middle line:90%
So they have to progress.

00:07:53.340 --> 00:07:55.580 align:middle line:84%
Now, those are two
very different examples

00:07:55.580 --> 00:07:58.340 align:middle line:84%
of a company that's willing
to look itself in the mirror

00:07:58.340 --> 00:08:00.670 align:middle line:84%
and admit, we're not
perfect, and we're

00:08:00.670 --> 00:08:03.790 align:middle line:84%
going to be honest about this,
and a company that stonewalls

00:08:03.790 --> 00:08:05.150 align:middle line:90%
and does the very opposite.

00:08:05.150 --> 00:08:10.350 align:middle line:84%
Now, one is on a high
purpose path, and one is not.

00:08:10.350 --> 00:08:17.500 align:middle line:84%
>>And in reality, isn't there
a positive psychological impact

00:08:17.500 --> 00:08:20.650 align:middle line:84%
when a company is
willing to admit

00:08:20.650 --> 00:08:22.590 align:middle line:84%
the error of their
ways, their sins?

00:08:22.590 --> 00:08:25.860 align:middle line:84%
Doesn't everybody love a
repentant sinner in life?

00:08:25.860 --> 00:08:27.250 align:middle line:90%
>>They do.

00:08:27.250 --> 00:08:31.010 align:middle line:84%
That is a very sexy story,
the idea of rebirth,

00:08:31.010 --> 00:08:34.570 align:middle line:84%
of rejuvenation, of waking
up and seeing the light, so

00:08:34.570 --> 00:08:36.740 align:middle line:84%
to speak, and then
acting in accordance

00:08:36.740 --> 00:08:40.100 align:middle line:84%
with this new perspective,
this new worldview.

00:08:40.100 --> 00:08:41.820 align:middle line:90%
That's a very powerful story.

00:08:41.820 --> 00:08:43.940 align:middle line:90%
It can rejuvenate a brand.

00:08:43.940 --> 00:08:49.200 align:middle line:84%
It can rejuvenate employees'
loyalty, better workforce.

00:08:49.200 --> 00:08:51.760 align:middle line:84%
It can certainly win
customer affinity,

00:08:51.760 --> 00:08:53.840 align:middle line:84%
and help a company
to better compete.

00:08:53.840 --> 00:08:56.750 align:middle line:84%
So it's actually a
very positive process.

00:08:56.750 --> 00:08:59.720 align:middle line:84%
>>Let's go into some specific
examples of companies

00:08:59.720 --> 00:09:01.980 align:middle line:84%
that have taken a good
long look at themselves,

00:09:01.980 --> 00:09:06.920 align:middle line:84%
and they've confessed, and they
have changed policy procedure,

00:09:06.920 --> 00:09:09.970 align:middle line:84%
whatever, and then look
at where it's taken them.

00:09:09.970 --> 00:09:12.760 align:middle line:84%
>>Well, a really great
example is a smaller company

00:09:12.760 --> 00:09:14.890 align:middle line:84%
called Green Mountain
Coffee Roasters.

00:09:14.890 --> 00:09:17.730 align:middle line:84%
Green Mountain Coffee Roasters
is based in New England.

00:09:17.730 --> 00:09:21.930 align:middle line:84%
They're actually an incredibly
fast-- They're a company that's

00:09:21.930 --> 00:09:24.275 align:middle line:84%
growing very quickly, growing
at a rate of about 16%

00:09:24.275 --> 00:09:27.880 align:middle line:84%
a year because,
about 17 years ago,

00:09:27.880 --> 00:09:32.120 align:middle line:84%
the CEO of that company,
Bob Stiller, decided, gee,

00:09:32.120 --> 00:09:34.270 align:middle line:90%
we're a gourmet coffee company.

00:09:34.270 --> 00:09:37.720 align:middle line:84%
I'm going to go visit the
coffee plantations in Guatemala

00:09:37.720 --> 00:09:40.070 align:middle line:84%
and Mexico that
supply our beans.

00:09:40.070 --> 00:09:40.820 align:middle line:90%
So he did.

00:09:40.820 --> 00:09:42.210 align:middle line:90%
He got in a plane.

00:09:42.210 --> 00:09:43.900 align:middle line:84%
He went to visit some
of the plantations

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:46.540 align:middle line:84%
where his coffee beans
were being supplied.

00:09:46.540 --> 00:09:48.300 align:middle line:90%
Sorry, I can't speak today.

00:09:48.300 --> 00:09:52.370 align:middle line:84%
And he told me he was shocked
at the level of poverty

00:09:52.370 --> 00:09:53.920 align:middle line:90%
and devastation.

00:09:53.920 --> 00:09:56.920 align:middle line:84%
He actually got
very emotional when

00:09:56.920 --> 00:09:58.450 align:middle line:90%
he was describing this scenario.

00:09:58.450 --> 00:10:02.203 align:middle line:84%
He's like, people
do not realize there

00:10:02.203 --> 00:10:03.570 align:middle line:90%
were people were starving.

00:10:03.570 --> 00:10:06.390 align:middle line:84%
There were children that
were clearly uneducated,

00:10:06.390 --> 00:10:09.670 align:middle line:84%
unable to be educated,
and not receiving

00:10:09.670 --> 00:10:10.974 align:middle line:90%
any sort of healthcare.

00:10:10.974 --> 00:10:12.390 align:middle line:84%
People were living
in the streets.

00:10:12.390 --> 00:10:16.320 align:middle line:84%
These people, their
culture, their society,

00:10:16.320 --> 00:10:19.340 align:middle line:84%
their socioeconomic
structure has deteriorated

00:10:19.340 --> 00:10:23.190 align:middle line:84%
because they've
been growing coffee

00:10:23.190 --> 00:10:25.210 align:middle line:90%
for centuries, literally.

00:10:25.210 --> 00:10:28.240 align:middle line:84%
And many American and
European coffee companies

00:10:28.240 --> 00:10:31.020 align:middle line:84%
refuse to pay them a fair
price for their beans.

00:10:31.020 --> 00:10:36.080 align:middle line:84%
So what it costs them to produce
coffee is not even paid for.

00:10:36.080 --> 00:10:39.000 align:middle line:84%
The price the market's
willing to bear

00:10:39.000 --> 00:10:41.170 align:middle line:84%
does not exceed
the price of labor.

00:10:41.170 --> 00:10:46.430 align:middle line:84%
So that is causing major
deterioration and catastrophe.

00:10:46.430 --> 00:10:48.870 align:middle line:84%
There are millions of people
affected by this problem.

00:10:48.870 --> 00:10:53.300 align:middle line:84%
So Bob got back on a plane,
went back to his home base

00:10:53.300 --> 00:10:57.270 align:middle line:84%
and told everyone, and
dedicated his company

00:10:57.270 --> 00:10:59.455 align:middle line:84%
to being a leader in
what's called fair trade.

00:10:59.455 --> 00:11:01.760 align:middle line:84%
The fair trade movement
in the United States,

00:11:01.760 --> 00:11:03.600 align:middle line:90%
very progressive.

00:11:03.600 --> 00:11:05.430 align:middle line:10%
Consumers should get involved.

00:11:05.430 --> 00:11:08.270 align:middle line:10%
It really-- it's about
companies standing up and going,

00:11:08.270 --> 00:11:12.010 align:middle line:10%
we're going to pay people a fair
price because this is connected

00:11:12.010 --> 00:11:13.700 align:middle line:10%
to so many problems,
human rights

00:11:13.700 --> 00:11:15.700 align:middle line:10%
problems, political problems.

00:11:15.700 --> 00:11:18.820 align:middle line:84%
Bob Stiller told me it's
connected to world peace.

00:11:18.820 --> 00:11:20.480 align:middle line:90%
So this is a huge problem.

00:11:20.480 --> 00:11:23.910 align:middle line:84%
Well, since he's done that, his
coffee quality has increased.

00:11:23.910 --> 00:11:27.240 align:middle line:84%
His employees have become
much more loyal and happy,

00:11:27.240 --> 00:11:28.710 align:middle line:90%
as have his consumers.

00:11:28.710 --> 00:11:31.680 align:middle line:84%
And that is one of the
world's fastest growing,

00:11:31.680 --> 00:11:34.290 align:middle line:84%
well, the nation's fastest
growing coffee companies.

00:11:34.290 --> 00:11:36.750 align:middle line:84%
Like I said, they're
growing at about 16% a year.

00:11:36.750 --> 00:11:38.987 align:middle line:90%
That's extremely fast.

00:11:38.987 --> 00:11:41.070 align:middle line:84%
>>And they're inspiring
change within the industry

00:11:41.070 --> 00:11:43.105 align:middle line:84%
for the other coffee
providers as well.

00:11:43.105 --> 00:11:43.980 align:middle line:90%
>>I mean, absolutely.

00:11:43.980 --> 00:11:46.070 align:middle line:84%
>>Doesn't Starbucks even
have fair trade blends?

00:11:46.070 --> 00:11:50.514 align:middle line:84%
>>Sure, now Starbucks and
Dunkin' Donuts and Procter

00:11:50.514 --> 00:11:52.180 align:middle line:84%
and Gamble's brands
are looking into it.

00:11:52.180 --> 00:11:54.780 align:middle line:90%
So I think there's movement.

00:11:54.780 --> 00:11:56.530 align:middle line:90%
But they embraced this.

00:11:56.530 --> 00:11:58.370 align:middle line:84%
Bob Stiller and
Green Mountain Coffee

00:11:58.370 --> 00:12:01.370 align:middle line:84%
embraced fair
trade 16 years ago.

00:12:01.370 --> 00:12:02.670 align:middle line:90%
That's a long time ago.

00:12:02.670 --> 00:12:04.470 align:middle line:90%
That's before it was en vogue.

00:12:04.470 --> 00:12:06.210 align:middle line:84%
That's before anybody
else was doing it.

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:09.260 align:middle line:84%
And everyone looked at them
and went, you're crazy!

00:12:09.260 --> 00:12:10.590 align:middle line:90%
What are you talking about?

00:12:10.590 --> 00:12:11.900 align:middle line:90%
Why do you care?

00:12:11.900 --> 00:12:13.909 align:middle line:84%
And how can you
make as much money?

00:12:13.909 --> 00:12:15.450 align:middle line:84%
But he really believed
that he could,

00:12:15.450 --> 00:12:17.970 align:middle line:84%
and he's actually proven
all the critics wrong.

00:12:17.970 --> 00:12:20.560 align:middle line:90%
>>And I've met him.

00:12:20.560 --> 00:12:22.460 align:middle line:84%
I'm very impressed with
him as a human being.

00:12:22.460 --> 00:12:25.740 align:middle line:84%
And it was a person that
made these changes coming

00:12:25.740 --> 00:12:26.360 align:middle line:90%
from heart.

00:12:26.360 --> 00:12:30.040 align:middle line:84%
And this heart element seems
to be a big piece that's

00:12:30.040 --> 00:12:31.570 align:middle line:84%
been missing in the
corporate world.

00:12:31.570 --> 00:12:32.380 align:middle line:90%
>>It really is.

00:12:32.380 --> 00:12:35.895 align:middle line:84%
>>Could it be coming more
toward the forefront now?

00:12:35.895 --> 00:12:37.060 align:middle line:90%
>>I certainly have never--

00:12:37.060 --> 00:12:41.810 align:middle line:84%
I was flabbergasted, surprised
to talk to people, CEOs

00:12:41.810 --> 00:12:44.970 align:middle line:84%
or chairmen, like Ray Anderson,
the chairman of Interface

00:12:44.970 --> 00:12:47.930 align:middle line:84%
or Bob Stiller or Anita
Roddick from the Body Shop,

00:12:47.930 --> 00:12:50.810 align:middle line:84%
or I mean even Lord
John Brown or Debra

00:12:50.810 --> 00:12:52.630 align:middle line:84%
Dunn from Hewlett
Packard, these people

00:12:52.630 --> 00:12:58.560 align:middle line:84%
had a level of fire and
passion about this and heart.

00:12:58.560 --> 00:13:02.230 align:middle line:84%
And they expressed that
sort of moral intelligence

00:13:02.230 --> 00:13:06.210 align:middle line:84%
and harnessed that in terms
of the way they led companies.

00:13:06.210 --> 00:13:07.680 align:middle line:90%
It's a new brand of leadership.

00:13:07.680 --> 00:13:10.840 align:middle line:84%
And it's absolutely
changing categories.

00:13:10.840 --> 00:13:14.510 align:middle line:84%
It's changing the quality of
life for millions of people.

00:13:14.510 --> 00:13:16.280 align:middle line:84%
>>It doesn't have
to be the greatest

00:13:16.280 --> 00:13:18.290 align:middle line:84%
fear of their
board of directors.

00:13:18.290 --> 00:13:21.260 align:middle line:84%
>>No, in fact their board
